<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="438" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1582,2041]" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,481,1690,1717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Diagnosis. Male imago.</emphasis>
1) sternum IX with posterior margin almost straight (
<figureCitation box="[1103,1196,1690,1717]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
); 2) pedestal of each side touching basally, inner projection short, thick, almost rounded, and with outer margin straight, outer projection short, slender and with apex broadly pointed (
<figureCitation box="[660,841,1762,1789]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Figs 2D and 2H</figureCitation>
); 3) base of penis wide proximally, narrowing toward apex (
<figureCitation box="[220,407,1798,1825]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Figs 2D and 2H</figureCitation>
); 4) main lobe of penis bladelike, slightly curved ventrally and with distoventral gonopore (
<figureCitation box="[159,281,1834,1861]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Figs 2D–I</figureCitation>
); 5) penis apex with expansion curved outwards (
<figureCitation box="[856,977,1834,1861]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Figs 2D–I</figureCitation>
); 6) secondary lobe completely reduced (
<figureCitation box="[159,278,1870,1897]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Figs 2D–I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="440" pageId="3" pageNumber="438" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1582,2041]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,933]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="440" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,1906,1933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Description. Male imago.</emphasis>
Length (n=1, mm): body, 7.8; fore wing, 5.7; hind wing, 2.4. General coloration yellowish grey (
<figureCitation box="[331,420,1942,1969]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="438">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Head completely shaded with black dorsally, ventrally whitish, slightly tinged with black. Antenna with scape and pedicel grey, flagellum lost. Thorax. Pronotum shaded with gray, with paler transversal line on posterior margin; prosternum whitish, propleura whitish, shaded with gray. Mesonotum yellowish white with blackish medial line, parapsidal suture and posteroscutal protuberance slightly shaded with gray; pleura and sterna whitish, shaded with black; and gray around coxa. Metanotum yellowish. Legs. Foreleg greyish, except distal tarsomere and claws slightly paler. Middle and hind legs yellowish. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[942,1121,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">Figs 2B and 2C</figureCitation>
). Fore wing with membrane hyaline, shaded with light grey on C and Sc areas; veins grey; cross veins hyaline; MP 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1118,1126,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">2</subScript>
not connected to IMP, ICu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">1</subScript>
not connected to CuA, ICu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[454,462,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">2</subScript>
directly connected to CuA. Hind wing similar to fore wing, but paler; intercalary vein of radial sector very short. Abdomen whitish translucent, shaded with gray, except medial line, intersegmental membranes, and lateral transversal dash on terga II–VII (
<figureCitation box="[737,826,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) Abdominal sterna whitish, shaded with gray on inner margin of gill sclerites and very slightly on meson of sterna VII–IX. Genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1034,1154,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">Figs 2D–I</figureCitation>
): sternum IX with almost straight posterior margin; pedestal of each side touching basally, inner projection short, thick, almost rounded, and with outer margin straight, outer projection short, slender and with apex broadly pointed; base of penis wide proximally, narrowing toward apex; main lobe of penis slender, bladelike and sclerotized, slightly curved ventrally and with distoventral gonopore, inner margin of apex (
<figureCitation box="[768,983,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[235,1350,186,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[230,1358,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsurus fortuitus sp. nov. male imago.A. dorsal view; B. forewing; C. hind wing; D. half of genitalia in ventral view; E. half of genitalia in ventrolateral view; F. half of genitalia in lateral view; G. penis ventral view - twisted in stereoscope (paratype); H. genitalia in ventral view; I. genitalia in lateral view. (eco = expansion curved outwards)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6201857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6201857/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="440">Figures 2D and 2E</figureCitation>
) with expansion curved outwards (eco), secondary lobe completely reduced, apical half of penis orangish. (Caudal filaments broken off and lost)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
